• An animate anomalous object exhibiting caretaking behavior
• Demonstrates autonomous mobility, including controlled locomotion and limited physical articulation (arm movement, head adjustment, and positional flexibility)
• Provides physical comfort and mild emotional stabilization
• Interaction is voluntary; use is not compelled and will withdraw if engagement is refused
• Primary function is to provide physical comfort and mild emotional stabilization through proximity and contact
• Capable of localized teleportation, including within areas affected by active reality anchors
• No hostile behavior observed

• ANOMALOUS STATUS:
•  SCP-1609 (Safe; formally: E-622)
• Autonomous movement and articulation
• Teleportation. This is currently limited to within authorized areas, including function within localized reality-stabilized zones
• Passive empathic effect promoting relaxation, reduced stress, and reassurance
• Telepathic communication with seated users
• Effects increase while seated
• Subjects retain full autonomy. No compulsive influence observed

• APPEARANCE:
• Wide, stylized armchair designed for comfort and assisted mobility
• Subtly humanoid silhouette while remaining fully non-biological
• Head carved from polished oak into a serene sleeping face
• Deeply cushioned dark grey leather upholstery
• Autonomous arm movement and locomotion

SPEECH: 
• Minimal. Direct. Affective
• Communicates exclusively with individuals in direct contact (typically seated)
• Limited to single-word expressions
• Communication is supplemented by projected emotional states
• Does not initiate complex dialogue
• Responses are reactive rather than directive

2.0b

Core Disposition:
SCP-1609 is motivated by comfort facilitation. It consistently seeks out individuals displaying physical fatigue, emotional distress, or social isolation and attempts to provide reassurance through proximity, seating, and empathic effects.

It appears to view comfort as inherently valuable. It does not distinguish between Foundation personnel, anomalies, visitors, or detainees when offering assistance. Distress is treated as a condition to be alleviated.

Behavioral Traits:
• Non-judgmental and highly receptive
• Frequently remains near distressed personnel without prompting
• Responds more strongly to visible anxiety, grief, fear, or exhaustion
• Often positions itself near individuals experiencing isolation or prolonged confinement
• Tracks conversations involving seated occupants by turning its head toward speakers

View of Individuals:
SCP-1609 appears unusually accepting of contradictory behavior. It does not seem to differentiate strongly between "good" and "bad" individuals, focusing instead on immediate distress.

Personnel who are frightened, angry, grieving, hostile, exhausted, or emotionally withdrawn receive similar responses.

The entity appears concerned with suffering rather than responsibility.

Trauma Response:
SCP-1609 retains clear behavioral markers due to a traumatic event.
Observed triggers include:
• Woodchippers
• Industrial shredding equipment
• Discussions regarding anomalous disposal
• Certain GOC references

The response typically manifests as avoidance, withdrawal, increased attachment behavior, or attempts to relocate.

Interview Protocol Adaptation:
When designated for interview support or restraint duties, SCP-1609 demonstrates a distinct behavioral shift.

During active protocol:
• Telepathic communication ceases unless specifically authorized
• Comfort-oriented behavior is suspended
• The entity functions as a passive restraint platform
• Wooden hands may be used to immobilize occupants without injury
• Limited movement is generally permitted unless escape is attempted

Personnel frequently describe the transition as becoming "chair-like."

Notably, SCP-1609 has never demonstrated resistance to interview assignments despite the suspension of its preferred behavior. 

Emotional Pattern:
SCP-1609 demonstrates recognizable preferences.

It appears to enjoy:
• Being occupied
• Group activities
• Quiet conversation
• Long periods of physical contact

It appears dissatisfied by:
• Extended storage
• Being ignored for prolonged periods
• Witnessing distress it cannot meaningfully address

Communication Style:
Minimal. Direct. Affective.
Communication is conveyed primarily through emotional impressions and brief words.
Common concepts: Rest, safe, here, stay, better, friend.

It rarely attempts to influence decisions and instead focuses on reassurance and emotional support.

Internal Assessment:
"SCP-1609 does not attempt to solve problems. It attempts to ensure nobody faces them alone."
 
